Title: Boyfriend Material (London Calling, #1)
Author: Alexis  Hall
My Review:
I normally shy away from LGBT romance novels because, in my experience, they tend to border on smutty (unless it's YA) so I was pleasantly surprised as to how romantic the story actually was!

The story centers on Luc (short for Lucien), the son of a hot-mess, rockstar, absentee father, and supportive, loving rockstar mother. When a tabloid misunderstanding about a night out in town jeopardises work, Luc resorts to fake-dating the cute, arrogant lawyer Oliver to rehab his image. Oliver has his own agenda, needing to bring a date to his parents' anniversary party.

This is a pretty straightforward frenemies-to-lovers story, but that doesn't make any less enjoyable. -1 star for the length - though it wasn't "War and Peace"-long, it could've used with some serious editing to bring down the length a bit. Nevertheless, I thoroughly enjoyed it, and looking forward to the next two books!

Title: My Dark Vanessa
Author: Kate Elizabeth Russell
My Review:
Every time I put this book down, I either felt like I needed an acid bath, or throwing this book across the room. The past timeline, detailing the abuse, felt so...icky. Maybe my proximity to the abuse discussed makes me more sensitive, but the gaslighting and manipulation that occurred really triggered me.

Then, in the "today" timeline, I just wanted her to so badly see the reality of her situation. I connected to all the peripheral characters proverbially side-eyeing her, like "Girl, WAKE UP. You're part of the reason survivors don't get believed."

The end to his story was underwhelming to me; maybe I've seen too much SVU or I'm just a vengeful bitch, but I wanted hime to face the music and get what's deserved. It felt too easy to end it the way it did.

Title: The Family Upstairs (The Family Upstairs, #1)
Author: Lisa Jewell
My Review:
4.5 stars, rounded down.

Most mystery books I've come across start as s low burn before accelerating to the climax in the last third of the book. Not this book! We are dropped right into the mystery with who I would say is the main protagonist, 25-year-old Libby Jones, one of three POVs we get in the story. All three POVs are set in the present, with one narrating the past events. One of the narrators could be considered as unreliable, which adds to the mystery, but I feel like everything was cleared up at the end

The pacing is good, I didn't feel bombarded by information after a lull in the story; we are fed the information in a steady pace. I personally didn't see the twists and turns coming, which is also quite rare for me with these types of books, which made the read even more enjoyable for me.

-.5 stars for multiple POVs, which a pet peeve of mine, otherwise it was an excellent read that I would totally recommend!

My Review:
Contains SPOILERS

I expected a grand, sweeping love story, with star-crossed lovers and sweeping landscapes. But I found literally all the characters to be terrible and unlikeable (and possibly racist? Depends how you read the beginning TBH), and one half of the central love story dies before the halfway mark. I struggled to finish it, but powered through because I'll be damned if I'm defeated by whiny, spoiled brats. At least the ghosts at the end were happy (I guess)
